  <h2>What Is Metacognition?</h2>

  <p>
    Metacognition is about children knowing themselves as learners. It helps them recognise what they find easy and what they find difficult, so they can adapt how they approach tasks.
  </p>

  <p>
    A child might realise, "I understand this poem better when I read it out loud," or an older pupil might think, "I need to re-read this section before I can answer these questions."
  </p>

  <p>
    It also involves self-regulation: monitoring progress and adjusting along the way. A pupil who self-regulates does not give up when things get difficult. They step back, think about what is not working, and try a different approach.
  </p>

  <figure class="img-wide">
    <img src={asset('/images/teacher-pupils.jpg')} alt="A teacher working with pupils at ISJ" loading="lazy" class="w-full" />
