  <h2>Planning, Monitoring, Evaluating</h2>

  <p>
    ISJ teachers encourage children to move through three stages in every task:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Planning</strong> — Before starting, pupils think about what they want to achieve and how they might go about it. What do they already know? What resources might help?</li>
    <li><strong>Monitoring</strong> — While working, pupils learn to check their progress. "Am I on the right track? What do I do when I get stuck?"</li>
    <li><strong>Evaluating</strong> — After finishing, pupils reflect on how things went. "What worked well? What could I improve next time?"</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Reflection turns every task, whether it went well or not, into a learning experience.
  </p>

  <h2>Why It Matters</h2>

  <p>
    Metacognitive skills help children become more thoughtful, confident, and independent learners. These skills transfer well beyond school: into problem-solving, decision-making, and the ability to face challenges with resilience.
  </p>

  <blockquote>
    <p>"Too often, we think of intelligence as a fixed commodity. Metacognitive skills are among the most transferable skills students can develop."</p>
  </blockquote>
  <p class="text-[length:var(--text-xs)] text-charcoal-muted -mt-4 mb-6">Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD), 2014</p>

  <h2>Supporting Metacognition at Home</h2>

  <p>
    Parents can reinforce these habits with simple reflection questions after homework or projects:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>"What part did you find easiest or trickiest?"</li>
    <li>"What helped you when you got stuck?"</li>
    <li>"What would you do differently next time?"</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    These conversations remind children that mistakes are part of the process, and that understanding how you learn is as valuable as what you learn.
  </p>

